Basic Networking Commands (With Explanation)
1Ô∏è‚É£ ip addr

Shows IP addresses of all interfaces.

ip addr


Useful for checking IP, subnet mask, interfaces.

2Ô∏è‚É£ ip link

Shows network interfaces and their state.

ip link show


Enable/disable an interface:

sudo ip link set eth0 up
sudo ip link set eth0 down

3Ô∏è‚É£ ip route

Shows routing table.

ip route


Add a route:

sudo ip route add 192.168.20.0/24 via 192.168.1.1

4Ô∏è‚É£ ping

Checks connectivity to another host.

ping google.com

5Ô∏è‚É£ curl

Checks if a service/website is reachable (HTTP/S).

curl -I https://google.com

6Ô∏è‚É£ ss (socket statistics)

Replaces netstat, shows open ports.

ss -tulnp

7Ô∏è‚É£ nmcli

NetworkManager CLI tool (RHEL/CentOS/Rocky/Amazon Linux).

View connections:

nmcli connection show


Add new connection:

nmcli connection add con-name static-ip ifname eth0 type ethernet ipv4.addresses 192.168.1.10/24 ipv4.gateway 192.168.1.1 ipv4.dns 8.8.8.8 ipv4.method manual

8Ô∏è‚É£ hostnamectl

Check and set system hostname.

hostnamectl status
hostnamectl set-hostname webserver01

9Ô∏è‚É£ systemctl status network

Used on older systems where network service runs.

üîü tcpdump

Capture packets on an interface.

sudo tcpdump -i eth0


Capture only port 443:

sudo tcpdump -i eth0 port 443

üüß 2. Real-Time Scenarios + Commands
üü© Scenario 1: Server is not reachable (Ping fails)
Steps to troubleshoot:
1. Check IP
ip addr

2. Check interface status
ip link show

3. Restart network
sudo systemctl restart NetworkManager

4. Check firewall
sudo firewall-cmd --state
sudo firewall-cmd --list-all

5. Check routing
ip route

üü© Scenario 2: DNS not resolving

Symptoms:
Can ping IP but not domain name.

Fix:

Check /etc/resolv.conf

cat /etc/resolv.conf


Add DNS server:

echo "nameserver 8.8.8.8" | sudo tee -a /etc/resolv.conf


Test:

ping google.com

üü© Scenario 3: Two servers cannot communicate

Check firewall:

sudo firewall-cmd --list-ports


Open a port:

sudo firewall-cmd --add-port=8080/tcp --permanent
sudo firewall-cmd --reload


Check SELinux block:

sudo setenforce 0


If works ‚Üí add permanent rule in /etc/selinux/config

üü© Scenario 4: Web page not loading but server is up

Check if port is open:

ss -tulnp | grep 80


Check firewall:

sudo firewall-cmd --add-service=http --permanent
sudo firewall-cmd --reload


Check SELinux:

sudo getenforce

üü© Scenario 5: Add a static IP to a RHEL server
nmcli connection modify eth0 \
ipv4.addresses 192.168.1.50/24 \
ipv4.gateway 192.168.1.1 \
ipv4.dns 8.8.8.8 \
ipv4.method manual

nmcli connection up eth0

üü• 3. Issues + Solutions
‚ùå Issue: No Internet but local ping works
Solution:

Check DNS.

cat /etc/resolv.conf


Add:

nameserver 8.8.8.8

‚ùå Issue: Interface down after reboot
Solution:
nmcli con mod eth0 connection.autoconnect yes

‚ùå Issue: Duplicate IP conflict
Solution:

Check ARP:
arp -a

Change IP:
nmcli con mod eth0 ipv4.addresses 192.168.1.80/24
nmcli con up eth0

‚ùå Issue: Service listening on wrong interface
Solution:

Check service:

ss -tulnp


Fix config:

listen 0.0.0.0:8080


Restart:

systemctl restart <service>
